As shown in Fig. 13
, for both HH-alloys the power factor of the HP sample is much higher than for the HPT-processed samples. In contrast to this observation, the thermal conductivity of the HPT-processed samples, even after annealing, is only about half of the thermal conductivity of the HP sample (Fig. 14
); its phonon part reaches ultra-low values especially for Ti0.5Zr0.5NiSn0.98Sb0.02 (2 – 0.5 mW/cmK in the temperature range measured).

Regarding the grain size distribution, TEM investigations of thin lamellae of NbFeSb give the same impression as SEM investigations (Fig. 17
), but show the microstructure in more detail. The dislocation density (Fig. 18
, bottom) in the HP sample is as low as about 2–3 × 1013 m−2. After HPT, dense clusters of dislocations are observed, and the dislocation density is increased by about one order of magnitude to 5–8 × 1014 m−2. During annealing a partial recrystallization and recovery of the remaining volume takes place. Therefore the majority of the volume is recrystallized with fine grains and a low dislocation density of 5 × 1013 m−2, but in some parts only not all dislocations were able to anneal out so that in these regions the dislocation density remains in a range of 4 × 1014 m−2 (Fig. 18, bottom).
